**Windows:**

To programmatically list all running applications on a Windows desktop, you can use the following methods:

### 1. Using the `tasklist` command

You can use the `tasklist` command in the Windows Command Prompt to get a list of all running processes. Here's an example:

```bash
tasklist /v /fo csv
```

This will output a CSV-formatted list of all running processes, including their PID, name, session name, session ID, memory usage, and status.

### 2. Using the `GetProcesses` method in .NET

You can use the `GetProcesses` method in the `System.Diagnostics` namespace to get a list of all running processes. Here's an example in C#:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Diagnostics;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Process[] processes = Process.GetProcesses();
        foreach (Process process in processes)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(process.ProcessName);
        }
    }
}
```

This will output a list of all running process names.

### 3. Using the `EnumProcesses` function in C++

You can use the `EnumProcesses` function in the Windows API to get a list of all running processes. Here's an example:

```cpp
#include <Windows.h>
#include <iostream>

int main()
{
    DWORD aProcesses[1024];
    DWORD cbNeeded;
    DWORD cProcesses;

    if (!EnumProcesses(aProcesses, sizeof(aProcesses), &cbNeeded))
    {
        return 1;
    }

    cProcesses = cbNeeded / sizeof(DWORD);

    for (DWORD i = 0; i < cProcesses; i++)
    {
        HANDLE hProcess = OpenProcess(PROCESS_QUERY_INFORMATION | PROCESS_VM_READ, FALSE, aProcesses[i]);
        if (hProcess != NULL)
        {
            char szProcessName[MAX_PATH];
            if (GetModuleBaseNameA(hProcess, NULL, szProcessName, MAX_PATH))
            {
                std::cout << szProcessName << std::endl;
            }
            CloseHandle(hProcess);
        }
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This will output a list of all running process names.

